<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-279-906  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 279 906.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  March 19 1990 v9 n6 p120(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>GE, 2 employees guilty in fraud. (General Electric Co. and oneemployee guilty of overcharging the Army on the DecentralizedAutomated Service-3 battlefield computer contract; anotheremployee guilty of covering up the fraud)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Green, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   General Electric Co. (cases).andO;Ticker:    GE.andO;Topic:     MilitaryGovernment AgencyCourt CasesFraudGovernment ContractsDefense ContractsUnited States. Army.andO;Person:    Leo, Gerald A. (cases); Badolato, James (cases).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>GE, 2 Employees Guilty in FraudandM;After 12 weeks of testimony and six days of deliberations, a U.S.andP;  DistrictCourt jury in Philadelphia recently found the General Electric Co. and one ofits employees guilty of fraudulently overcharging the Army $8 million on abattlefield computer contract.andP;  A second GE employee was convicted ofcovering up the fraud.andM;David Howard, assistant U.S.andP;  attorney for the Eastern District ofPennsylvania, said that under the verdict, GE likely will repay up to $10million.andP;  The company also could be fined as much as $20 million.andM;GE was found guilty on four of five counts of mail fraud and of having made281 false claims to the government.andM;Gerald A. Leo, a GE materials manager, was found guilty on four of fivecounts of mail fraud and one count of submitting a false claim.andP;  He faces upto 25 years in jail and a $1 million fine.andP;  The jury, however, found Leo notguilty of racketeering.andM;James Badolato, a GE contract administration employee, was found guilty ofdeliberately misleading government auditors and submitting false documents.andO;He faces a possible 10 years in jail and a $500,000 fine.andP;  Badolato also wasfound not guilty of racketeering.andM;GE vice president Philip A. Lacovara said no senior GE official had approvedthe fraudulent deals and the company should not be held accountable.andM;He said the company voluntarily returned $3.7 million to the government in1985.andP;  The company will appeal the verdict, he said.andM;The verdict stems from a 1979 contract in which GE provided hardware for theArmy's Decentralized Automated Service-3 program, a mobile battlefieldcomputer system.andP;  Leo and Badolato negotiated lower prices with about 30subcontractors, but they submitted 240 invoices containing the higheroriginal prices to the government.andO;</TEXT></DOC>